As Section 2.2 introduced and illustrated in Fig. 3, clustering of the impedance-sensitive parameters into three distinctive sensitivity groups, i.e. CT sensitive, Warburg sensitive or both CT and Warburg sensitive, was done considering the ratio (
                              γ
                           ) between the maximum sensitivity indices of the CT (H and M frequency bands) and Warburg regions (L frequency band). Table 3 summarises the parameter clustering based on the above-mentioned sensitivity ratio. The sensitivity ratio (
                              γ
                           ) bounds of 3 and 0.3 were assumed to cluster the parameters with at least 3 times higher sensitivity indices with respect to either Warburg (for CT-sensitive parameters) or CT (for Warburg-sensitive) regions.

On the other hand, the fixed parameters excluded from the tuning process can be obtained without opening the cell; some can be directly measured or estimated, whilst others can be obtained from the literature. Geometric parameters such as electrode surface area (
                              A
                           ) and thicknesses (
                              L
                           ) can be determined without cell tear-down procedures and by implementing optical measurements [2]. Whilst electrode conductivities (
                              σ
                           ) are directly measurable, electrolyte-related parameters (


                                    κ


                                    e


                            and 


                                    D


                                    l


                                    e


                           ) can be obtained from literature as, in most situations, it is practically difficult to extract any electrolyte from a commercial cell by opening. Maximum ionic concentration (


                                    c


                                    s


                           ) and active material volume fraction (


                                    ϵ


                                    s


                           ) of electrodes can be found in the literature for similar electrode chemistries, or the latter can be estimated through a comparison of the theoretical electrode density and the actual density [22].

